main event: An unidentified bright object with a halo of diffused light was observed by the crew of a C-119 aircraft over Tunis, Libya on February 11, 1953.
interesting points: The object appeared very bright and was observed at 17,000 feet, making an indicated airspeed of 170 knots.
The length of the sighting varied from 5 to 55 minutes, and several crew members stated the object appeared to ascend and descend slowly.
Four out of the five crew members believed the object was not a star, while the remaining observer would not commit to a conclusion.
Project Blue Book submitted the case to an astrophysicist, who determined the object was likely the planet Venus, which would appear very bright under the fair weather conditions.
The fact that the object remained almost stationary and was observed for a long period of time supported the conclusion that it was Venus.
sighted object: A bright object with a halo of diffused light
